Road Safety Audit—Belmont Street (Route 123) at Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue—Brockton, MA
A Road Safety Audit for the intersection of Belmont Street (Route 123), Linwood Street and Lorraine
Avenue in the City of Brockton was held on September 1, 2009 at the Old Colony Planning Council
office. As indicated in Table 1, the audit team consisted of representatives from Federal, State, Regional
and Local agencies as well as abutters and included a cross-section of engineering, planning and
Road Safety Audit—Belmont Street (Route 123) at Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue—Brockton, MA
The Federal Highway Administration defines a Road Safety Audit (RSA) as the formal safety
examination of an existing or future road or intersection by an independent, multidisciplinary team. The
purpose of an RSA is to identify potential safety issues and possible opportunities for safety
improvements considering all roadway users. The Old Colony Planning Council (OCPC) requested that
MassHighway conduct a Road Safety Audit of the intersection of Belmont Street (Route 123) at Linwood
Street and Lorraine Avenue in the City of Brockton. The intersection has been identified by OCPC as a
high crash location, and is #68 on MassHighway’s statewide list of the Top Crash Intersections from 2005
to 2007. As such, an RSA was conducted in order to identify potential both short and long term safety
improvements that can be made at the subject intersection.
The intersection of Belmont Street (Route 123), Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue, shown in Figure 1,
is located in the western portion of Brockton. Belmont Street is a state-owned roadway functionally
classified as an Urban Minor Arterial. Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue are City-owned roadways,
each functionally classified as an Urban Collector. Belmont Street is a significant regional roadway,
connecting Brockton with neighboring communities Easton and Abington. Route 123 connects to Route
24 approximately ½ mile west of the study intersection, and is one of the major arterial routes providing
access from Route 24 to downtown Brockton.

At the time of the audit, crash records provided by the Brockton Police Department were incomplete.
Complete crash records for a three year period are critical to the audit process not only to evaluate the
intersection based on the number and severity of crashes, but also to analyze the prevalent trends among
crashes to determine which potential safety improvements would provide the greatest benefit to help
alleviate crashes at a high crash location. MassHighway provided background information about the
crash history at the intersection, which is included in the Appendix. The intersection ranked 68
MassHighway’s statewide list of the Top Crash Intersections from 2005 to 2007. This ranking is based
on the number of crashes in MassHighway’s database which can be georeferenced to a cluster area around
the intersection. This cluster area experienced 56 crashes in the three year period. Twenty-five of the 56
crashes involved an injury. The ranking is based on a weighted system which calculates the Equivalent
Property Damage Only (EPDO) rating of the intersection. Fatal crashes are weighted 10 times and injury
crashes are weighted 5 times. There were no fatal crashes in the three year study period.
Town officials, emergency responders and abutters present at the audit offered some personal
observations as to what contributes to the number of crashes at the intersection. High traffic volumes
cause turning vehicles to take chances on unacceptable gaps. Belmont Street through vehicles have been
observed in both directions stopping in the outside lane to allow vehicles to turn from Linwood Street or
Lorraine Avenue; the turning vehicle subsequently collides with a vehicle passing in the inside lane after
passing the stopped vehicle. Additionally, the tight corner radii contribute to crashes because larger
vehicles and inexperienced drivers encroach on the second lane when turning from the side streets.
Automatic Traffic Recorder (ATR) counts and Manual Turning Movement (MTM) counts were provided
by OCPC. ATR data were recorded in 2009 at the intersection. Belmont Street (Route 123) carries

23,700 vehicles per day (vpd) east of Linwood Street and 23,800 vpd west of Linwood Street. Linwood
Street carries 3,700 vpd, while Lorraine Avenue carries 1,800 vpd. MTM data were recorded in 2008 for
both the AM and PM peak periods. The AM peak hour occurred from 7:15 to 8:15 AM. During the AM
peak hour, there were 103 left turns from Linwood Street to Belmont Street westbound, against 1,716
through vehicles on Belmont Street (920 eastbound, 796 westbound). There were 89 left turns from
Belmont Street westbound to Linwood Street. The PM peak hour occurred from 5:00 to 6:00 PM.
During the PM peak hour, there were 69 left turns from Linwood Street to Belmont Street westbound,
against 2,458 through vehicles on Belmont Street (1,267 eastbound, 1,191 westbound). There were 178
left turns from Belmont Street westbound to Linwood Street. These conflicting volumes, combined with
the high speed of travel on Belmont Street, result in very few acceptable gaps for those turning vehicles.
OCPC performed capacity analysis based on the 2008 MTM count data. The analyses showed that the
intersection operates at Level of Service “F” during the morning and afternoon peak hours. OCPC also
concluded that the intersection satisfies the Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD)
It should be noted that there were a relatively low number of “through” vehicles crossing from Linwood
Street to Lorraine Avenue, or vice versa, during either the AM or PM peak period. In the AM peak hour,
seven vehicles crossed from Lorraine Avenue to Linwood Street and 16 vehicles crossed from Linwood
Street to Lorraine Avenue. In the PM peak hour, 18 vehicles crossed from Lorraine Avenue to Linwood
Street and eight vehicles crossed from Linwood Street to Lorraine Avenue.

Following a brief introduction to the RSA process and a summary of traffic volumes and crash
information, the audit participants were asked to discuss issues that may affect safety at the intersection of
Belmont Street (Route 123), Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue. Audit participants then conducted a
site visit as a group, at which time they offered observations on safety concerns and deficiencies. A
summary of those major safety considerations is as follows:
Geometrics/Alignment –Belmont Street has narrow lanes with no shoulders, which
provides little room for error given the volume of traffic on Belmont Street. Tight corner
radii on three of the four corners also contribute to safety issues, as turning vehicles
sometimes encroach on multiple lanes. The offset alignment of Linwood Street and
Lorraine Avenue was also cited as a safety concern, as vehicles intending to cross the
intersection must wait for appropriate gaps required to make back-to-back turning
Sight Distance – Linwood Street is not readily visible to Belmont Street eastbound traffic,
which decreases awareness for approaching vehicles of the possibility that other vehicles
are making a turn or are stopped waiting to turn. Concerns were also raised regarding
vegetation and utility poles restricting visibility for vehicles departing both Linwood
Roadway Condition – There were a number of concerns raised regarding the condition of
existing features at the intersection. Pavement markings are faded along Belmont Street
in the vicinity of Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue. The pavement is in poor
condition along Belmont Street, with rutting and potholes in the outside lane. Poor
drainage and poor lighting were also cited as a concern along Belmont Street. It was
noted that the pavement condition and drainage issues sometimes cause vehicles traveling
in the outside lane to encroach on the inside lane in an attempt to avoid these issues.
Access Management – There are a significant number of driveway openings and areas
with no curb definition along Belmont Street. It was suggested that these create a safety
Pedestrian accommodations – Existing sidewalks are in fair condition along both sides of
Belmont Street, with crosswalks crossing Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue but no
crosswalk across Belmont Street. Audit participants suggested that there is a fair amount
of pedestrian traffic in the area. Pedestrian activity is generated by Brockton High
School, which is approximately ¼ mile east of the study intersection, and Veterans
Hospital, which is approximately ¼ mile west of the study intersection. It was noted that
a number of pedestrians from the Veterans Hospital are wheelchair-bound, magnifying
the importance of providing pedestrian facilities that are ADA-compliant.

After the site visit, audit participants returned to the meeting location to discuss the safety issues and
consider improvements. Audit participants were encouraged to consider both short and long term
improvements for each issue. Each improvement considered has been categorized as short-term, mid­
term, or long-term based on the definitions shown in Table 2. Additionally, a cost category has been
assigned to each improvement based on the parameters set forth in Table 2.

improvements at Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue to these improvements, which are
• Increase corner radii. Three of the four corners at the intersection have tight corner radii, which
increases the potential for encroachment of turning vehicles. It is recommended that the corner
radii be increased on the southwest corner of Belmont Street and Linwood Street, and on both
corners of Belmont Street and Lorraine Avenue. This is a medium cost, short term improvement.
It should be noted that this may require relocation of the crosswalk and stop line further back
from Belmont Street on both Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue, which may increase sight
distance concerns for vehicles exiting from those streets.

close the existing driveway that is currently blocked by boulders, which was supported by the
owner of the restaurant who was present at the audit. This is a short term, low cost improvement.
• Improve curb reveal. Although curb is present along Belmont Street for most of its length within
the project area, curb reveals are substandard, likely due to past pavement overlays and
settlement. This creates a safety concern because it decreases roadway definition and reduces the
physical barrier between the roadway and the adjacent sidewalk or grass area. It is recommended
that curb be removed and reset along the corridor to reestablish a standard 6” reveal, and that
broken or damaged curb be replaced in conjunction with this improvement. This is a short term,
• Add left turn lane for Belmont Street westbound. There are a significant number of vehicles
turning from Belmont Street westbound to Linwood Street. A dedicated left turn lane would

westbound traffic. This would require widening and would likely require property acquisition by
the state. Due to the significant amount of opposing traffic on Belmont Street eastbound, this
improvement should only be considered in conjunction with installation of a traffic signal.
• Realign Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue. It was suggested that Linwood Street and Lorraine
Avenue be realigned to form a typical 4-way intersection, with Linwood Street and Lorraine
Avenue directly opposite one another. This would require property acquisition by both the state
and the City and would significantly impact the property on the southwest corner of the
intersection. It should be noted that the property owner was present at the audit and said that he
would be amenable to potential alignment changes dependent upon the exact impact to his
property. This would be a long term, high cost improvement and is only recommended if done in
• Install fully actuated traffic signal. The installation of a fully actuated traffic signal would
provide a protected phase for vehicles turning from Linwood Street or Lorraine Avenue. Traffic
signal installation could be completed independent of geometric improvements, or could be done
in conjunction with widening and installation of a left turn lane and/or in conjunction with
realignment of Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue. Traffic signal installation within existing
geometry would require the use of split phasing, in which both Linwood Street and Lorraine
Avenue are provided with separate protected green phases. Traffic signal installation in
conjunction with realignment would provide more intersection capacity, as the side streets could
then be served with the same green phase which in turn provides a greater percentage of the
overall cycle length for Belmont Street traffic. Traffic signal installation is a high cost, mid to
long term improvement, dependent on the level of geometric improvements.
• Move stop lines closer to intersection. Vehicles were observed creeping past the stop line and
beyond the crosswalk while waiting for an acceptable gap to turn onto Belmont Street. It was
suggested that the stop lines be moved closer to the intersection to address this issue. This
improvement is not feasible because the stop line must be a minimum of 4 feet behind the
crosswalk, and existing crosswalk locations are dictated by the sidewalks and wheelchair ramps
The following improvements were suggested by audit participants to alleviate sight distance concerns at
the intersection of Belmont Street, Linwood Street and Lorraine Avenue.

outdated and do not meet current Manual on Uniform Traffic Control Devices (MUTCD)
standards for retroreflectivity. It is recommended that existing street signs be replaced with new
signs that meet MUTCD retroreflectivity standards, with 6” minimum letter height. This is a

Several audit participants discussed concerns regarding the condition of the existing roadway as
contributors to safety issues at the study intersection. Recommended improvements are as follows:
• Repaint lane lines along Belmont Street. The existing pavement markings on Belmont Street are
faded, which may contribute to crashes caused by lane violations and vehicle encroachment. It is
recommended that all existing pavement markings be repainted within 300’ in each direction of
the intersection. Replacement markings should be 6 inches in width in adherence to current
MassHighway standards. This is a short-term, low cost improvement.
• Improve drainage. Several audit participants noted there are puddles that form along the gutter
line during storms. This causes vehicles traveling in the outside lane to encroach on the inside
lane in order to avoid the puddles. It is recommended that the existing drainage system be
inspected and reviewed to identify any improvements that may eliminate ponding water, and that
existing catch basins be cleaned of sediment and debris. This is a short-term, medium cost

• Rehabilitate pavement. In addition to drainage deficiencies, several audit participants suggested
that poor existing pavement conditions cause vehicles traveling in the outside lane to encroach on
the inside lane. Cracking and settlement is visible on Belmont Street, especially along the outside
westbound lane. The pavement should be rehabilitated along the corridor, either by milling and
overlay or by asphalt reclamation. Pavement cores should be performed first to determine the
necessary course of action. This is a mid-term, high cost improvement.
• Improve roadway lighting. It was suggested by abutters present at the audit that existing lighting
is insufficient for the area, and that existing lights along Belmont Street are either not on or need
bulb replacements. It is recommended that MassHighway investigate existing lighting conditions
at night and either replace bulbs or consider adding additional lights where warranted. This is a
There are a significant number of driveways and access points along Belmont Street in the vicinity of the
intersection. Several audit participants suggested that these driveways create a safety issue due to the
increased number of turning movements and conflicts created with turning vehicles. It is recommended
that MassHighway verify permits against existing driveway openings. This is a short-term, low cost
Several safety issues relating to pedestrian accommodations were discussed during the audit. As
previously mentioned, both Brockton High School and the Veterans Hospital contribute to pedestrian
activity in the area. Specific potential improvements are as follows:
• Reconstruct sidewalks and wheelchair ramps. Existing sidewalks along both sides of Belmont
Street within the vicinity of the intersection are primarily in fair condition but in some areas have
patches and settlement which pose difficulties for wheelchair-bound pedestrians. It was
suggested that some pedestrians in wheelchairs travel in the roadway gutter instead of using the
sidewalk, which creates a clear hazard due to the lack of shoulders along Belmont Street. It is
recommended that sidewalks be reconstructed within 300’ in each direction, and that new cement
concrete wheelchair ramps be constructed at the intersection meeting all ADA requirements. This
is a mid-term, high cost improvement.
• Signalization. There is no existing crossing that allows pedestrians to cross Belmont Street in the
vicinity of the intersection. Due to the high traffic volumes along Belmont Street, a crosswalk is
not feasible unless done in conjunction with installation of a traffic signal, which is a mid-term,
high cost improvement. A traffic signal would provide a protected pedestrian phase with
